member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Type
member.summary: Gets the name of the type as specified by schema.org.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.About
member.summary: The subject matter of the content.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Abstract
member.summary: An abstract is a short description that summarizes a CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessibilityAPI
member.summary: Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessibilityControl
member.summary: Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessibilityFeature
member.summary: Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessibilityHazard
member.summary: A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3 (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessibilitySummary
member.summary: A human-readable summary of specific accessibility features or deficiencies, consistent with the other accessibility metadata but expressing subtleties such as "short descriptions are present but long descriptions will be needed for non-visual users" or "short descriptions are present and no long descriptions are needed."

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessMode
member.summary: The human sensory perceptual system or cognitive faculty through which a person may process or perceive information. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual, colorDependent, chartOnVisual, chemOnVisual, diagramOnVisual, mathOnVisual, musicOnVisual, textOnVisual.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccessModeSufficient
member.summary: A list of single or combined accessModes that are sufficient to understand all the intellectual content of a resource. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AccountablePerson
member.summary: Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AggregateRating
member.summary: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AlternativeHeadline
member.summary: A secondary title of the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.AssociatedMedia
member.summary: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Audience
member.summary: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Audio
member.summary: An embedded audio object.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Author
member.summary: The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Award
member.summary: An award won by or for this item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Character
member.summary: Fictional person connected with a creative work.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Citation
member.summary: A citation or reference to another creative work, such as another publication, web page, scholarly article, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Comment
member.summary: Comments, typically from users.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.CommentCount
member.summary: The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.ConditionsOfAccess
member.summary:
Conditions that affect the availability of, or method(s) of access to, an item. Typically used for real world items such as an ArchiveComponent held by an ArchiveOrganization. This property is not suitable for use as a general Web access control mechanism. It is expressed only in natural language.

For example "Available by appointment from the Reading Room" or "Accessible only from logged-in accounts ".

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.ContentLocation
member.summary: The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.ContentRating
member.summary: Official rating of a piece of content—for example,'MPAA PG-13'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.ContentReferenceTime
member.summary: The specific time described by a creative work, for works (e.g. articles, video objects etc.) that emphasise a particular moment within an Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Contributor
member.summary: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.CopyrightHolder
member.summary: The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.CopyrightYear
member.summary: The year during which the claimed copyright for the CreativeWork was first asserted.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Correction
member.summary: Indicates a correction to a CreativeWork, either via a CorrectionComment, textually or in another document.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.CreativeWorkStatus
member.summary: The status of a creative work in terms of its stage in a lifecycle. Example terms include Incomplete, Draft, Published, Obsolete. Some organizations define a set of terms for the stages of their publication lifecycle.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Creator
member.summary: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.DateCreated
member.summary: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.DateModified
member.summary: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.DatePublished
member.summary: Date of first broadcast/publication.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.DiscussionUrl
member.summary: A link to the page containing the comments of the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Editor
member.summary: Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.EducationalAlignment
member.summary: An alignment to an established educational framework.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.EducationalUse
member.summary: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Encoding
member.summary: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.EncodingFormat
member.summary:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see IANA site and MDN reference) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, encoding can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular encodingFormat information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.ExampleOfWork
member.summary: A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Expires
member.summary: Date the content expires and is no longer useful or available. For example a VideoObject or NewsArticle whose availability or relevance is time-limited, or a ClaimReview fact check whose publisher wants to indicate that it may no longer be relevant (or helpful to highlight) after some date.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Funder
member.summary: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Genre
member.summary: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.HasPart
member.summary: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that is part of this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Headline
member.summary: Headline of the article.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.InLanguage

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.InteractionStatistic

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.InteractivityType

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.IsAccessibleForFree

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.IsBasedOn

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.LocationCreated

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Mentions

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWorkAndSeries.Offers

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.CharacterAttribute

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.CountriesSupported
member.summary: Countries for which the application is supported. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

member.summary: If the file can be downloaded, URL to download the binary.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.FeatureList
member.summary: Features or modules provided by this application (and possibly required by other applications).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.FileSize
member.summary: Size of the application / package (e.g. 18MB). In the absence of a unit (MB, KB etc.), KB will be assumed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.GameItem
member.summary: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.GameLocation
member.summary: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.InstallUrl

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.MemoryRequirements
member.summary: Minimum memory requirements.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.NumberOfPlayers
member.summary: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.Permissions

member.name: P:Schema.NET.GameAndSoftwareApplication.ProcessorRequirements

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganization.OpeningHours
member.summary:
The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.

  • Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su.
  • Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as 15:00.
  • Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>.
  • If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganization.OwnershipFundingInfo
member.summary: For an Organization (often but not necessarily a NewsMediaOrganization), a description of organizational ownership structure; funding and grants. In a news/media setting, this is with particular reference to editorial independence. Note that the funder is also available and can be used to make basic funder information machine-readable.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganization.PublishingPrinciples
member.summary:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via URL) a document describing the editorial principles of an Organization (or individual e.g. a Person writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a CreativeWork (e.g. NewsArticle) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the CreativeWork.

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a funder) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoContains
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a containing geometry to a contained geometry. "a contains b iff no points of b lie in the exterior of a, and at least one point of the interior of b lies in the interior of a". As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoCoveredBy
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that covers it. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoCovers
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a covering geometry to a covered geometry. "Every point of b is a point of (the interior or boundary of) a". As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoCrosses
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that crosses it: "a crosses b: they have some but not all interior points in common, and the dimension of the intersection is less than that of at least one of them". As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoDisjoint
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically disjoint: they have no point in common. They form a set of disconnected geometries." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in DE-9IM)

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoEquals
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically equal, as defined in DE-9IM. "Two geometries are topologically equal if their interiors intersect and no part of the interior or boundary of one geometry intersects the exterior of the other" (a symmetric relationship)

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoIntersects
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) have at least one point in common. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoOverlaps
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that geospatially overlaps it, i.e. they have some but not all points in common. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoTouches
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) touch: they have at least one boundary point in common, but no interior points." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in DE-9IM )

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndOrganizationAndPlace.GeoWithin
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to one that contains it, i.e. it is inside (i.e. within) its interior. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoContains
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a containing geometry to a contained geometry. "a contains b iff no points of b lie in the exterior of a, and at least one point of the interior of b lies in the interior of a". As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoCoveredBy
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that covers it. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoCovers
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a covering geometry to a covered geometry. "Every point of b is a point of (the interior or boundary of) a". As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoCrosses
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that crosses it: "a crosses b: they have some but not all interior points in common, and the dimension of the intersection is less than that of at least one of them". As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoDisjoint
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically disjoint: they have no point in common. They form a set of disconnected geometries." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in DE-9IM)

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoEquals
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically equal, as defined in DE-9IM. "Two geometries are topologically equal if their interiors intersect and no part of the interior or boundary of one geometry intersects the exterior of the other" (a symmetric relationship)

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoIntersects
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) have at least one point in common. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoOverlaps
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that geospatially overlaps it, i.e. they have some but not all points in common. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoTouches
member.summary: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) touch: they have at least one boundary point in common, but no interior points." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in DE-9IM )

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.GeoWithin
member.summary: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to one that contains it, i.e. it is inside (i.e. within) its interior. As defined in DE-9IM.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.LocalBusinessAndPlace.OpeningHours
member.summary:
The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.

  • Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su.
  • Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as 15:00.
  • Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>.
  • If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.OrganizationAndPlace.PublishingPrinciples
member.summary:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via URL) a document describing the editorial principles of an Organization (or individual e.g. a Person writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a CreativeWork (e.g. NewsArticle) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the CreativeWork.

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a funder) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICourseInstance.Instructor

member.name: T:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork
member.summary: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.About
member.summary: The subject matter of the content.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Abstract
member.summary: An abstract is a short description that summarizes a CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessibilityAPI
member.summary: Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessibilityControl
member.summary: Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessibilityFeature
member.summary: Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessibilityHazard
member.summary: A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3 (WebSchemas wiki lists possible values).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessibilitySummary
member.summary: A human-readable summary of specific accessibility features or deficiencies, consistent with the other accessibility metadata but expressing subtleties such as "short descriptions are present but long descriptions will be needed for non-visual users" or "short descriptions are present and no long descriptions are needed."

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessMode
member.summary: The human sensory perceptual system or cognitive faculty through which a person may process or perceive information. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual, colorDependent, chartOnVisual, chemOnVisual, diagramOnVisual, mathOnVisual, musicOnVisual, textOnVisual.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccessModeSufficient
member.summary: A list of single or combined accessModes that are sufficient to understand all the intellectual content of a resource. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AccountablePerson
member.summary: Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AggregateRating
member.summary: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AlternativeHeadline
member.summary: A secondary title of the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.AssociatedMedia
member.summary: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Audience
member.summary: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Audio
member.summary: An embedded audio object.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Author
member.summary: The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Award
member.summary: An award won by or for this item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Character
member.summary: Fictional person connected with a creative work.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Citation
member.summary: A citation or reference to another creative work, such as another publication, web page, scholarly article, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Comment
member.summary: Comments, typically from users.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.CommentCount
member.summary: The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ConditionsOfAccess
member.summary:
Conditions that affect the availability of, or method(s) of access to, an item. Typically used for real world items such as an ArchiveComponent held by an ArchiveOrganization. This property is not suitable for use as a general Web access control mechanism. It is expressed only in natural language.

For example "Available by appointment from the Reading Room" or "Accessible only from logged-in accounts ".

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ContentLocation
member.summary: The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ContentRating
member.summary: Official rating of a piece of content—for example,'MPAA PG-13'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ContentReferenceTime
member.summary: The specific time described by a creative work, for works (e.g. articles, video objects etc.) that emphasise a particular moment within an Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Contributor
member.summary: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.CopyrightHolder
member.summary: The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.CopyrightYear
member.summary: The year during which the claimed copyright for the CreativeWork was first asserted.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Correction
member.summary: Indicates a correction to a CreativeWork, either via a CorrectionComment, textually or in another document.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.CreativeWorkStatus
member.summary: The status of a creative work in terms of its stage in a lifecycle. Example terms include Incomplete, Draft, Published, Obsolete. Some organizations define a set of terms for the stages of their publication lifecycle.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Creator
member.summary: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.DateCreated
member.summary: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.DateModified
member.summary: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.DatePublished
member.summary: Date of first broadcast/publication.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.DiscussionUrl
member.summary: A link to the page containing the comments of the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Editor
member.summary: Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.EducationalAlignment
member.summary: An alignment to an established educational framework.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.EducationalUse
member.summary: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Encoding
member.summary: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.EncodingFormat
member.summary:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see IANA site and MDN reference) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, encoding can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular encodingFormat information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ExampleOfWork
member.summary: A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Expires
member.summary: Date the content expires and is no longer useful or available. For example a VideoObject or NewsArticle whose availability or relevance is time-limited, or a ClaimReview fact check whose publisher wants to indicate that it may no longer be relevant (or helpful to highlight) after some date.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Funder
member.summary: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Genre
member.summary: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.HasPart
member.summary: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that is part of this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Headline
member.summary: Headline of the article.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.InLanguage
member.summary: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the IETF BCP 47 standard. See also availableLanguage.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.InteractionStatistic
member.summary: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.InteractivityType
member.summary: The predominant mode of learning supported by the learning resource. Acceptable values are 'active', 'expositive', or 'mixed'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.IsAccessibleForFree
member.summary: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.IsBasedOn
member.summary: A resource from which this work is derived or from which it is a modification or adaption.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.IsFamilyFriendly
member.summary: Indicates whether this content is family friendly.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.IsPartOf
member.summary: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense), is part of.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Keywords
member.summary: Keywords or tags used to describe this content. Multiple entries in a keywords list are typically delimited by commas.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.LearningResourceType
member.summary: The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.License
member.summary: A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.LocationCreated
member.summary: The location where the CreativeWork was created, which may not be the same as the location depicted in the CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.MainEntity
member.summary: Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Material
member.summary: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.MaterialExtent
member.summary: The quantity of the materials being described or an expression of the physical space they occupy.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Mentions
member.summary: Indicates that the CreativeWork contains a reference to, but is not necessarily about a concept.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Offers
member.summary: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Position
member.summary: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Producer
member.summary: The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, tv/radio series etc.).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Provider
member.summary: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Publication
member.summary: A publication event associated with the item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Publisher
member.summary: The publisher of the creative work.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.PublisherImprint
member.summary: The publishing division which published the comic.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.PublishingPrinciples
member.summary:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via URL) a document describing the editorial principles of an Organization (or individual e.g. a Person writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a CreativeWork (e.g. NewsArticle) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the CreativeWork.

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a funder) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.RecordedAt
member.summary: The Event where the CreativeWork was recorded. The CreativeWork may capture all or part of the event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ReleasedEvent
member.summary: The place and time the release was issued, expressed as a PublicationEvent.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Review
member.summary: A review of the item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.SchemaVersion
member.summary: Indicates (by URL or string) a particular version of a schema used in some CreativeWork. For example, a document could declare a schemaVersion using an URL such as http://schema.org/version/2.0/ if precise indication of schema version was required by some application.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.SdDatePublished
member.summary: Indicates the date on which the current structured data was generated / published. Typically used alongside sdPublisher

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.SdLicense
member.summary: A license document that applies to this structured data, typically indicated by URL.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.SdPublisher
member.summary: Indicates the party responsible for generating and publishing the current structured data markup, typically in cases where the structured data is derived automatically from existing published content but published on a different site. For example, student projects and open data initiatives often re-publish existing content with more explicitly structured metadata. The sdPublisher property helps make such practices more explicit.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.SourceOrganization
member.summary: The Organization on whose behalf the creator was working.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Spatial
member.summary: The "spatial" property can be used in cases when more specific properties (e.g. locationCreated, spatialCoverage, contentLocation) are not known to be appropriate.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.SpatialCoverage
member.summary: The spatialCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the place(s) which are the focus of the content. It is a subproperty of contentLocation intended primarily for more technical and detailed materials. For example with a Dataset, it indicates areas that the dataset describes: a dataset of New York weather would have spatialCoverage which was the place: the state of New York.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Sponsor
member.summary: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Temporal
member.summary: The "temporal" property can be used in cases where more specific properties (e.g. temporalCoverage, dateCreated, dateModified, datePublished) are not known to be appropriate.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.TemporalCoverage
member.summary:
The temporalCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the period that the content applies to, i.e. that it describes, either as a DateTime or as a textual string indicating a time period in ISO 8601 time interval format. In the case of a Dataset it will typically indicate the relevant time period in a precise notation (e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 would be written "2011/2012"). Other forms of content e.g. ScholarlyArticle, Book, TVSeries or TVEpisode may indicate their temporalCoverage in broader terms - textually or via well-known URL. Written works such as books may sometimes have precise temporal coverage too, e.g. a work set in 1939 - 1945 can be indicated in ISO 8601 interval format format via "1939/1945".

Open-ended date ranges can be written with ".." in place of the end date. For example, "2015-11/.." indicates a range beginning in November 2015 and with no specified final date. This is tentative and might be updated in future when ISO 8601 is officially updated.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.ThumbnailUrl

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.TimeRequired

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.TranslationOfWork

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.Translator

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWork.TypicalAgeRange

member.summary: A human-readable summary of specific accessibility features or deficiencies, consistent with the other accessibility metadata but expressing subtleties such as "short descriptions are present but long descriptions will be needed for non-visual users" or "short descriptions are present and no long descriptions are needed."

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWork.AccessModeSufficient

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWork.Award

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWork.ConditionsOfAccess
member.summary:
Conditions that affect the availability of, or method(s) of access to, an item. Typically used for real world items such as an ArchiveComponent held by an ArchiveOrganization. This property is not suitable for use as a general Web access control mechanism. It is expressed only in natural language.

For example "Available by appointment from the Reading Room" or "Accessible only from logged-in accounts ".

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWork.Contributor

member.name: P:Schema.NET.CreativeWork.EncodingFormat
member.summary:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see IANA site and MDN reference) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, encoding can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular encodingFormat information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.ICreativeWorkSeries
member.summary:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike ItemList which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing TVSeries, RadioSeries, MovieSeries, BookSeries, Periodical and VideoGameSeries. In each case, the hasPart / isPartOf properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWorkSeries.Issn
member.summary: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

member.summary: The start date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ICreativeWorkSeries.EndDate
member.summary: The end date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

Unlike ItemList which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing TVSeries, RadioSeries, MovieSeries, BookSeries, Periodical and VideoGameSeries. In each case, the hasPart / isPartOf properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IDataCatalog.MeasurementTechnique
member.summary:
A technique or technology used in a Dataset (or DataDownload, DataCatalog), corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (described using variableMeasured). This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but rather as a high level summary for dataset discovery.

For example, if variableMeasured is: molecule concentration, measurementTechnique could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence".

If the variableMeasured is "depression rating", the measurementTechnique could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory".

If there are several variableMeasured properties recorded for some given data object, use a PropertyValue for each variableMeasured and attach the corresponding measurementTechnique.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IDemand.Gtin
member.summary: A Global Trade Item Number (GTIN). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes. The gtin property generalizes the earlier gtin8, gtin12, gtin13, and gtin14 properties. The GS1 digital link specifications express GTINs as URLs. A correct gtin value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a valid GS1 check digit and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also GS1's GTIN Summary and Wikipedia for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IDemand.Gtin12
member.summary: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IDemand.Gtin13
member.summary: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IDemand.Gtin14
member.summary: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IDemand.Gtin8
member.summary: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.

See also ineligibleRegion.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.EligibleTransactionVolume
member.summary: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.Gtin
member.summary: A Global Trade Item Number (GTIN). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes. The gtin property generalizes the earlier gtin8, gtin12, gtin13, and gtin14 properties. The GS1 digital link specifications express GTINs as URLs. A correct gtin value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a valid GS1 check digit and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also GS1's GTIN Summary and Wikipedia for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.Gtin12
member.summary: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.Gtin13
member.summary: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.Gtin14
member.summary: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.Gtin8
member.summary: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.IncludesObject
member.summary: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in the offer.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.IneligibleRegion
member.summary:
The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.

See also eligibleRegion.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.InventoryLevel

member.name: P:Schema.NET.Demand.Seller

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IEndorsementRating
member.summary:
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a "Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the result of an EndorseAction in which the object of the action is rated positively by some agent. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the Action.

An EndorsementRating may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive, endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IEngineSpecification
member.summary: Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEngineSpecification.EngineDisplacement
member.summary:
The volume swept by all of the pistons inside the cylinders of an internal combustion engine in a single movement.

Typical unit code(s): CMQ for cubic centimeter, LTR for liters, INQ for cubic inches * Note 1: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the valueReference property. * Note 2: You can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEngineSpecification.EnginePower
member.summary:
The power of the vehicle's engine. Typical unit code(s): KWT for kilowatt, BHP for brake horsepower, N12 for metric horsepower (PS, with 1 PS = 735,49875 W)

  • Note 1: There are many different ways of measuring an engine's power. For an overview, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horsepower#Enginepowertest_codes.
  • Note 2: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the valueReference property.
  • Note 3: You can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.

member.summary: The type of engine or engines powering the vehicle.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEngineSpecification.FuelType
member.summary: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEngineSpecification.Torque
member.summary:
The torque (turning force) of the vehicle's engine.

Typical unit code(s): NU for newton metre (N m), F17 for pound-force per foot, or F48 for pound-force per inch

  • Note 1: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined (e.g. reference RPM) using the valueReference property.
  • Note 2: You can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.

member.summary:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. member.name: T:Schema.NET.DrugCost
member.summary: The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory
member.summary: Categories that represent an assessment of the risk of fetal injury due to a drug or pharmaceutical used as directed by the mother during pregnancy.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory.FDAcategoryA
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that adequate and well-controlled studies have failed to demonstrate a risk to the fetus in the first trimester of pregnancy (and there is no evidence of risk in later trimesters).

member.name: F:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory.FDAcategoryB
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that animal reproduction studies have failed to demonstrate a risk to the fetus and there are no adequate and well-controlled studies in pregnant women.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory.FDAcategoryC
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that animal reproduction studies have shown an adverse effect on the fetus and there are no adequate and well-controlled studies in humans, but potential benefits may warrant use of the drug in pregnant women despite potential risks.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory.FDAcategoryD
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that there is positive evidence of human fetal risk based on adverse reaction data from investigational or marketing experience or studies in humans, but potential benefits may warrant use of the drug in pregnant women despite potential risks.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory.FDAcategoryX
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that studies in animals or humans have demonstrated fetal abnormalities and/or there is positive evidence of human fetal risk based on adverse reaction data from investigational or marketing experience, and the risks involved in use of the drug in pregnant women clearly outweigh potential benefits.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.DrugPregnancyCategory.FDAnotEvaluated
member.summary: A designation that the drug in question has not been assigned a pregnancy category designation by the US FDA.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign
member.summary: Design models for observational medical studies. Enumerated type.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.CaseSeries
member.summary: A case series (also known as a clinical series) is a medical research study that tracks patients with a known exposure given similar treatment or examines their medical records for exposure and outcome. A case series can be retrospective or prospective and usually involves a smaller number of patients than the more powerful case-control studies or randomized controlled trials. Case series may be consecutive or non-consecutive, depending on whether all cases presenting to the reporting authors over a period of time were included, or only a selection.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.CohortStudy
member.summary: Also known as a panel study. A cohort study is a form of longitudinal study used in medicine and social science. It is one type of study design and should be compared with a cross-sectional study. A cohort is a group of people who share a common characteristic or experience within a defined period (e.g., are born, leave school, lose their job, are exposed to a drug or a vaccine, etc.). The comparison group may be the general population from which the cohort is drawn, or it may be another cohort of persons thought to have had little or no exposure to the substance under investigation, but otherwise similar. Alternatively, subgroups within the cohort may be compared with each other.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.CrossSectional
member.summary: Studies carried out on pre-existing data (usually from 'snapshot' surveys), such as that collected by the Census Bureau. Sometimes called Prevalence Studies.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.Longitudinal
member.summary: Unlike cross-sectional studies, longitudinal studies track the same people, and therefore the differences observed in those people are less likely to be the result of cultural differences across generations. Longitudinal studies are also used in medicine to uncover predictors of certain diseases.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.Observational
member.summary: An observational study design.

member.name: F:Schema.NET.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.Registry
member.summary: A registry-based study design.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IEvent
member.summary: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the offers property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.About
member.summary: The subject matter of the content.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Actor
member.summary: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.AggregateRating
member.summary: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Attendee
member.summary: A person or organization attending the event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Audience
member.summary: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Composer
member.summary: The person or organization who wrote a composition, or who is the composer of a work performed at some event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Contributor
member.summary: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Director
member.summary: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.DoorTime
member.summary: The time admission will commence.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Duration
member.summary: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.EventStatus
member.summary: An eventStatus of an event represents its status; particularly useful when an event is cancelled or rescheduled.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Funder
member.summary: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.InLanguage
member.summary: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the IETF BCP 47 standard. See also availableLanguage.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.IsAccessibleForFree
member.summary: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Location
member.summary: The location of for example where the event is happening, an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.MaximumAttendeeCapacity
member.summary: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Offers
member.summary: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Organizer
member.summary: An organizer of an Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Performer
member.summary: A performer at the event—for example, a presenter, musician, musical group or actor.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.PreviousStartDate
member.summary: Used in conjunction with eventStatus for rescheduled or cancelled events. This property contains the previously scheduled start date. For rescheduled events, the startDate property should be used for the newly scheduled start date. In the (rare) case of an event that has been postponed and rescheduled multiple times, this field may be repeated.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.RecordedIn
member.summary: The CreativeWork that captured all or part of this Event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.RemainingAttendeeCapacity
member.summary: The number of attendee places for an event that remain unallocated.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Review
member.summary: A review of the item.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Sponsor
member.summary: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.StartDate
member.summary: The start date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.EndDate
member.summary: The end date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.SubEvent
member.summary: An Event that is part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each of which is a subEvent of the conference.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.SuperEvent
member.summary: An event that this event is a part of. For example, a collection of individual music performances might each have a music festival as their superEvent.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.Translator
member.summary: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.TypicalAgeRange
member.summary: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.WorkFeatured
member.summary: A work featured in some event, e.g. exhibited in an ExhibitionEvent. Specific subproperties are available for workPerformed (e.g. a play), or a workPresented (a Movie at a ScreeningEvent).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IEvent.WorkPerformed
member.summary: A work performed in some event, for example a play performed in a TheaterEvent.

member.summary: Any additional component of the exercise prescription that may need to be articulated to the patient. This may include the order of exercises, the number of repetitions of movement, quantitative distance, progressions over time, etc.

member.summary: How often one should break from the activity.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IFollowAction
member.summary:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:

  • BefriendAction: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is not necessarily reciprocal.
  • SubscribeAction: Unlike SubscribeAction, FollowAction implies that the follower acts as an active agent constantly/actively polling for updates.
  • RegisterAction: Unlike RegisterAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
  • JoinAction: Unlike JoinAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in getting updates from the object.
  • TrackAction: Unlike TrackAction, FollowAction refers to the polling of updates of all aspects of animate objects rather than the location of inanimate objects (e.g. you track a package, but you don't follow it).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IFollowAction.Followee
member.summary: A sub property of object. The person or organization being followed.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IFoodEstablishmentReservation.EndTime
member.summary:
The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.

Note that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IGeoShape.Box
member.summary: A box is the area enclosed by the rectangle formed by two points. The first point is the lower corner, the second point is the upper corner. A box is expressed as two points separated by a space character.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IGeoShape.Circle
member.summary: A circle is the circular region of a specified radius centered at a specified latitude and longitude. A circle is expressed as a pair followed by a radius in meters.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IGiveAction
member.summary:
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:

  • TakeAction: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
  • SendAction: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IItemList
member.summary: A list of items of any sort—for example, Top 10 Movies About Weathermen, or Top 100 Party Songs. Not to be confused with HTML lists, which are often used only for formatting.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IItemList.ItemListElement
member.summary:
For itemListElement values, you can use simple strings (e.g. "Peter", "Paul", "Mary"), existing entities, or use ListItem.

Text values are best if the elements in the list are plain strings. Existing entities are best for a simple, unordered list of existing things in your data. ListItem is used with ordered lists when you want to provide additional context about the element in that list or when the same item might be in different places in different lists.

Note: The order of elements in your mark-up is not sufficient for indicating the order or elements. Use ListItem with a 'position' property in such cases.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IItemList.ItemListOrder
member.summary: Type of ordering (e.g. Ascending, Descending, Unordered).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IItemList.NumberOfItems
member.summary: The number of items in an ItemList. Note that some descriptions might not fully describe all items in a list (e.g., multi-page pagination); in such cases, the numberOfItems would be for the entire list.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.ILocalBusiness
member.summary: A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ILocalBusiness.CurrenciesAccepted
member.summary:
The currency accepted.

Use standard formats: ISO 4217 currency format e.g. "USD"; Ticker symbol for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for Local Exchange Tradings Systems (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ILocalBusiness.OpeningHours
member.summary:
The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.

  • Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su.
  • Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as 15:00.
  • Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>.
  • If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ILocalBusiness.PaymentAccepted
member.summary: Cash, Credit Card, Cryptocurrency, Local Exchange Tradings System, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.ILocalBusiness.PriceRange
member.summary: The price range of the business, for example $$$.

For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMediaObject.StartTime
member.summary:
The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.

Note that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.MediaObject.EncodingFormat
member.summary:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see IANA site and MDN reference) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, encoding can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular encodingFormat information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IMedicalCause
member.summary: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMedicalCause.CauseOf
member.summary: The condition, complication, symptom, sign, etc. caused.

member.summary: One of a set of differential diagnoses for the condition. Specifically, a closely-related or competing diagnosis typically considered later in the cognitive process whereby this medical condition is distinguished from others most likely responsible for a similar collection of signs and symptoms to reach the most parsimonious diagnosis or diagnoses in a patient.

member.summary: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.

member.summary: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. member.summary: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. member.summary: A goal towards an action is taken. Can be concrete or abstract.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMedicalDevice.SeriousAdverseOutcome

Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

member.summary: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IMedicalStudy
member.summary: A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. member.name: T:Schema.NET.IMedicalTherapy
member.summary: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

member.summary: A contraindication for this therapy.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMedicalTherapy.DuplicateTherapy
member.summary: A therapy that duplicates or overlaps this one.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMedicalTherapy.SeriousAdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount
member.summary: A monetary value or range. This type can be used to describe an amount of money such as $50 USD, or a range as in describing a bank account being suitable for a balance between £1,000 and £1,000,000 GBP, or the value of a salary, etc. It is recommended to use PriceSpecification Types to describe the price of an Offer, Invoice, etc.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount.Currency
member.summary:
The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.

Use standard formats: ISO 4217 currency format e.g. "USD"; Ticker symbol for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for Local Exchange Tradings Systems (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount.MaxValue
member.summary: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount.MinValue
member.summary: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount.ValidFrom
member.summary: The date when the item becomes valid.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount.ValidThrough
member.summary: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.IMonetaryAmount.Value
member.summary:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

  • For QuantitativeValue and MonetaryAmount, the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
  • For PropertyValue, it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
  • Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
  • Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

member.name: T:Schema.NET.INewsArticle
member.summary:
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of schema.org News markup is also available.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.INewsArticle.Dateline
member.summary:
A dateline is a brief piece of text included in news articles that describes where and when the story was written or filed though the date is often omitted. Sometimes only a placename is provided.

Structured representations of dateline-related information can also be expressed more explicitly using locationCreated (which represents where a work was created e.g. where a news report was written). For location depicted or described in the content, use contentLocation.

Dateline summaries are oriented more towards human readers than towards automated processing, and can vary substantially. Some examples: "BEIRUT, Lebanon, June 2.", "Paris, France", "December 19, 2017 11:43AM Reporting from Washington", "Beijing/Moscow", "QUEZON CITY, Philippines".

member.name: P:Schema.NET.INewsArticle.PrintColumn
member.summary: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.INewsArticle.PrintEdition
member.summary: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.

member.name: P:Schema.NET.INewsArticle.PrintPage
member.summary: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).

member.name: P:Schema.NET.INewsArticle.PrintSection
member.summary: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.
